	<subsection xml:id="sec_counting_multiplication">
		<title>The Multiplication Rule</title>
		<p>In some instances, a process may have two or more steps, each of which can happen in several different ways. In order to determine the total number of ways that such a multi-step process can happen, we need to use a new rule, called the <term>multiplication rule</term>.</p>
		<definition xml:id="def_counting-rule_multiplication">
			<idx>multiplication rule (counting)</idx>
			<idx><h>counting rules</h><h>multiplication rule</h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>The <term>multiplication rule</term> states that if a process includes two steps where step one can happen in <m>n_1</m> ways and step two can happen in <m>n_2</m> ways, then the entire process can happen in <m>n_1 \times n_2</m> ways.</p>
				<p>This can be expanded to a process which includes <m>k</m> stages, the <m>i^\text{th}</m> of which can happen in <m>n_i</m> ways, then the total number of ways the process can happen is:
				<me>n_1 \times n_2 \times \cdots \times n_k</me>.</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>To see how this rule works, let's look at several examples.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_multiplication_2-step">
			<title>Applying the Multiplication Rule I</title>
			<statement>
				<p>A certain model of car comes in seven different colors, with a choice of 3 different engines. If you limit yourself to these options, how many different configurations are possible?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>The process of configuring the car has two steps:
					<ol>
						<li><p>Choose a color <mdash/> 7 choices</p></li>
						<li><p>Chose an engine <mdash/> 3 choices</p></li>
					</ol>
					So the total number of configurations is:
					<me>7 \times 3 = 21</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_multiplication_3-step">
			<title>Applying the Multiplication Rule II</title>
			<statement>
				<p>To put together your wardrobe on a certain morning, you must select from 5 pairs of slacks, 3 shirts, and 2 pairs of shoes. How many different outfits are possible?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>The process of putting together a wardrobe has three steps:
					<ol>
						<li><p>Choose your pants <mdash/> 5 different choices</p></li>
						<li><p>Choose your shirt <mdash/> 3 choices</p></li>
						<li><p>Choose your shoes <mdash/> only 2 choices</p></li>
					</ol>
					So the total number of outfits is:
					<me>5\times 3\times 2 = 30</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>Both of the examples above could be modeled using a tree diagram. A tree diagram is a useful way of picturing the multiplication rule. It can also be used to help us work through multiple-step problems that don't fit the multiplication rule above.</p>
		<definition xml:id="def_tree-diagram">
			<idx>tree diagram</idx>
			<statement>
				<p>In a <term>tree diagram</term>, each step in a process is represented by a set of branches leading to the possible outcomes in that step.</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
