			<answer><p>362880</p></answer>
		</exercise>
	</subsection>

	<subsection xml:id="sec_counting_permutations">
		<title>Permutations</title>
		<p>In some counting problems, we will find a process that looks much like the <q>factorial</q> questions from the last page, but in which we are not asked to use up or arrange all of the items. One such example can be found below.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_permutation_runners">
			<title>Ordering a Subset</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Suppose that ten runners compete in a race in which first, second, and third prizes are awarded. In how many ways can these prizes be won?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>Using the multiplication rule, the steps in this process are:
					<ol>
						<li><p>Award first prize to the winner (10 choices since anybody could win).</p></li>
						<li><p>Award second prize (9 choices since the winner is excluded).</p></li>
						<li><p>Award third prize (8 choices).</p></li>
					</ol>
					This gives the following total number of ways that the prizes can be won:
					<me>10\times 9\times 8 = 720</me>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>While the solution to this problem started off looking like a factorial, <m>10 \times 9 \times 8</m>, it stopped after 8 because we didn&apos;t need to order the remaining seven runners in this race. In general, when we need to count the number of ways to order or arrange <m>r</m> items chosen from <m>n</m> possible items, we are using a permutation.</p>
		<definition xml:id="def_permutation">
			<idx>permutation</idx>
			<idx><h>counting rules</h><h>permutation</h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>A <term>permutation</term> of n items taken r at a time is used to count the number of ways to arrange (or permute) <m>r</m> items chosen from <m>n</m> possible items. The formula for this permutation is:
				<me>P(n,r) = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!}</me>.</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>Applying this formula to the foot-race example above, we could have computed:
			<me>P(10,3) = \frac{10!}{(10-3)!} = \frac{10\times 9\times 8\times 7!}{7!} = 10\times 9\times 8 = 720</me>.
			Permutations are a general rule that can be used to count the number of ways to complete a process in which the order of completion matters. A race is a good example of when order matters. Another example can be found below.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_permutation_bands">
			<title>Using Permutations</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Six bands have expressed interest in performing at a concert with time slots for three performances. In how many ways can the concert manager make up a schedule for the concert?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>Since there are 6 bands to choose from, and only 3 are needed, and since the order of performance matters (changing the order would make a different schedule) the number of ways to schedule these bands is:
					<me>P(6,3) = \frac{6!}{3!} = 6\times 5\times 4 = 120</me>.</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>There are a few general rules which work no matter what <m>n</m> is used in a permutation. Three of these are shown below.
		  <ul>
		  	<li><p><m>P(n,n) = \frac{n!}{(n-n)!} = \frac{n!}{0!} = n!</m></p></li>
		  	<li><p><m>P(n,0) = \frac{n!}{(n-0)!} = \frac{n!}{n!} = 1</m></p></li>
		  	<li><p><m>P(n,1) = \frac{n!}{(n-1)!} = \frac{n\times (n-1)!}{(n-1)!} = n</m></p></li>
		  </ul>
		  Additionally, there is a short-cut that can be used instead of the formula. This is:
		  <me>P(n,r) = \underbrace{n\times (n-1) \times \cdots \times (n-r+1)}_{r \text { items}}</me>.
		</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_permutation_compute">
			<title>Computing Permutations</title>
			<statement>
				<p>Use the rules and short-cut seen above to find each of the following.
					<ol label="a" cols="3">
						<li><p><m>P(5,1)</m></p></li>
						<li><p><m>P(17,3)</m></p></li>
						<li><p><m>P(200,0)</m></p></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>The values of these expressions are:
					<ol label="a">
						<li><p><m>P(5,1) = 5</m> (the third rule above)</p></li>
						<li><p><m>P(17,3) = 17\times 16\times 15 = 4080</m> (short-cut formula above)</p></li>
						<li><p><m>P(200,0) = 1</m> (the second rule above)</p></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

