	<subsection xml:id="sec_counting_combinations">
		<title>Combinations</title>
		<p>Permutations are particularly useful when the order in which we select individuals makes a difference<mdash/>such as in running a race or creating a schedule. But order does not always matter, as seen in the next example.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_combination_movies">
			<title>Counting when Order Doesn&apos;t Matter</title>
			<statement>
				<p>You have two extra movie tickets and wish to share them with two of your four good friends. In how many ways can you pick the friends to go with you to the movies?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>Let&apos;s say that your friends names are: Alice, Bob, Candace, and David. If you try to count this using a permutation, you get:
					<me>P(4,2) = 4\times 3 = 12</me>.
					Unfortunately, this is not the correct answer. Consider the actual list of possible choices that this produces.</p>
				<table>
					<title>Possible Selections</title>
					<tabular>
						<row>
							<cell>AB</cell>
							<cell>AC</cell>
							<cell>AD</cell>
							<cell>BA</cell>
							<cell>BC</cell>
							<cell>BD</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell>CA</cell>
							<cell>CB</cell>
							<cell>CD</cell>
							<cell>DA</cell>
							<cell>DB</cell>
							<cell>DC</cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
				</table>
				<p>Notice that each pair appears twice. For example, AB and BA are counted separately. This is because in a permutation, the order in which we hand out the tickets makes a difference. But really, we don&apos;t care who got the first ticket<mdash/>we just want to know who is going. Since there are two of each possible pairs, the actual number of ways to pick the two friends to go with us is:
				<me>\frac{P(4,2)}{P(2,2)} = \frac{12}{2} = 6</me>.</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>In the example above, we arrived at the final solution using two steps. First, we counted the number of ways to pick the friends to go with us if the order did matter, in this case it was 12. Then we counted the number of ways that those two friends could be arranged, which was 2. Finally, we divide the 12 ordered ways by the 2 different orderings to get a total of 6 ways to choose our two friends if the order does not matter. This process can be combined into a single counting rule called a combination.</p>
		<definition xml:id="def_combination">
			<idx>combination</idx>
			<idx><h>counting rules</h><h>combination</h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>A <term>combination</term> of <m>n</m> items taken <m>r</m> at a time is used to count the number of ways to choose <m>r</m> items from <m>n</m> possible items if the order in which we select them does not matter. The formula for this combination is:
				<me>C(n,r) = \frac{P(n,r)}{r!} = \frac{n!}{r!(n-r)!}</me>.</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>
		<p>Applying this formula to the movie ticket example, we get:
			<me>C(4,2) = \frac{4!}{2!(4-2)!} = \frac{4\times 3\times 2!}{2!\times 2!} = \frac{4\times 3}{2\times 1} = 6</me>.</p>
		<p>Let&apos;s try applying this to another example.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_combination_committee">
			<title>Using a Combination</title>
			<statement>
				<p>A committee of 10 business executives wishes to choose a sub-committee of 3 to research a certain topic. In how many ways can this sub-committee be chosen?</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>The order in which a sub-committee is selected does not matter<mdash/>a person is either on the committee or not on the committee. Therefore, this is a combination and the solution is:
				<me>C(10,3) = \frac{10!}{3!(10-3)!} = \frac{10\times 9\times 8 \times 7!}{3!\times 7!} = \frac{10\times 9\times 8}{3\times 2\times 1} = 120</me>.</p>
			</solution>
		</example>
		<p>As with permutations, there are a few general rules that combinations follow no matter what the value of <m>n</m> is. Several of these rules are shown below.
		  <ul>
		  	<li><p><m>C(n,n) = 1</m></p></li>
		  	<li><p><m>C(n,1) = n</m></p></li>
		  	<li><p><m>C(n,r) = C(n,n-r)</m></p></li>
		  </ul></p>
		<p>And finally, a short-cut that can be easier to use than the formula above. 
		 	<me> C(n,r) = \frac{\overbrace{n\times (n-1) \times \cdots \times (n-r+1)}^{r \text{ values}}}{r!}</me>.</p>
		<p>We finish with an example of how these rules and shortcuts can be useful.</p>
		<example xml:id="examp_counting_combination_compute">
		 	<title>Computing Combinations</title>
		 	<statement>
		 		<p>Use the rules and short-cut seen above to find the value of each expression.
		 			<ol label="a" cols="2">
		 				<li><p><m>C(12,12)</m></p></li>
		 				<li><p><m>C(250,1)</m></p></li>
		 				<li><p><m>C(12,0)</m></p></li>
		 				<li><p><m>C(250,247)</m></p></li>
		 			</ol>
		 		</p>
		 	</statement>
		 	<solution>
		 		<p>Applying the rules and short-cut seen above, we get the following values.
		 			<ol label="a">
		 				<li><title><m>C(12,12) = 1</m></title><p>Here we use the first rule.  You could also recognize that there is only one way to pick all 12 of the 12 things we have</p></li>
		 				<li><title><m>C(250,1) = 250</m></title><p>We use the second rule.</p></li>
		 				<li><title><m>C(12,0) = C(12,12-0) = C(12,12) = 1</m></title><p>We use the third rule and (a) above.  We could also note that there is only 1 way to pick nothing</p></li>
		 				<li><title><m>C(250,247) = C(250,250-247) = C(250,3) = \frac{250\times 249\times 248}{3\times 2\times 1} = 2573000</m></title><p>We used the third rule and the shortcut formula.</p></li>
		 			</ol>
		 		</p>
		 	</solution>
		</example>

